<TEXT>
a fuel slick in the allegheny river slid 
past pittsburgh without entering the citys intake valves and the 
fastmoving oil posed little threat tuesday of fouling water 
downstream officials said 
nine oil booms were removed from the allegheny near freeport on 
tuesday said epa spokeswoman carrie deitzel another 16 booms will 
remain in the river 
the situation is good and its the best its been said carl 
kuehn deputy director of the pennsylvania emergency management 
agency 
federal state and local officials began formal investigations 
of the spill which began late friday 35 miles north of pittsburgh 
when at least 76000 gallons of diesel gasoline and kerosene 
spilled from a ruptured underground pipeline owned by the buckeye 
pipe line co 
buckeye said the ruptured pipeline was triggered by a landslide 
but charles duritsa regional director of the state department of 
environmental resources said residents near the spill site smelled 
fuel a day before the landslide 
there was speculation the leaking fuel weakened the ground and 
caused the slide he said 
officials on tuesday criticized the national transportation 
safety board which issues permits and regulates the nations 
pipeline system for not becoming involved in the cleanup and 
investigation 
we feel there is a need for further investigation we would 
like to see more indepth action by the ntsb kuehn said we 
are not happy with the response at this time 
communities downstream from the spill were forced to close the 
intake valves into their water treatment plants as the muck slowly 
moved downstream the spill at one time had threatened the water 
supplies of up to 1 million people along the allegheny and ohio 
rivers 
officials said small globs of the mixture from fuelsoaked soil 
will continue to seep into the allegheny at the ruptured pipeline 
near freeport the amounts appear to be insignificant but will be 
monitored continually said dave wright of the environmental 
protection agency 
</TEXT>
