<TEXT>
czechoslovakias bestread 
underground newspaper has published its first issue as a 
fullfledged daily and pledges to stay independent 
despite police harassment lidove noviny peoples news had 
circulated monthly in hundreds of selfpublished copies since 
december 1987 
it carried frequent contributions from such notable former 
dissidents as vaclav havel now president havel and jiri 
dienstbier now foreign minister 
during its underground existence the paper was granted 
exclusive interviews by late soviet dissident andrei sakharov 
president bush and other wellknown political figures angering the 
former communist authorities 
lidoves editor jiri ruml was the last of czechoslovakias 
leading dissidents to be released from prison only nine days after 
the countrys peaceful revolution began nov 17 
in its first issues this year the paper printed criticism of 
the communist party as well as the countrys strongest opposition 
force civic forum enhancing its image as the voice of 
freethinking people 
mondays first daily issue consisting of eight pages and a 
press run of 250000 copies carried a melange of news comment and 
opinion including articles about lithuania independence drive and 
german reunification plans 
political and commercial independence is a tenet of the paper 
there were offers from press tycoons like robert maxwell and 
rupert murdoch to buy stock in our paper but we rejected them 
ruml told a news conference last month we are not going to 
accept any capital from anyone 
the commercial side of the lidove noviny publishing project is 
supported by a line of some 30 publications including two books by 
havel and a large number of previously unpublished works by other 
dissidents 
looking back at 40 years of censorship by communist authorities 
ruml made it clear he wanted his paper to be different 
one of the main priorities is to revive the good language in 
which newspapers should be written not that communist journalese 
gibberish we have been reading so far he said 
</TEXT>
