<TEXT>
some foreign fruit and vegetable producers try 
to conform with us bans on certain pesticides but others often 
are unaware of restrictions according to a report to congress 
the general accounting office said monday it found that each of 
five countries checked has laws and regulations controlling 
pesticide availability and use by their own producers however 
those laws and regulations often dont mesh with us standards 
latin american and caribbean countries supply most of the fruits 
and vegetables imported by the united states in 1988 those 
totaled 55 million metric tons or 77 percent of total imports 
the five countries checked by gao the investigative arm of 
congress were chile costa rica dominican republic guatemala and 
mexico which accounted for more than half the 1988 produce imports 
exporters and producers in some of the countries try to use 
practices that take us pesticide restrictions into consideration 
the report said the gao found this to be done by multinational 
firms in all five countries and by other growers in chile and 
mexico 
where us requirements were not specifically considered in 
selecting pesticides for use on exports particularly among the 
less experienced growers in costa rica the dominican republic and 
guatemala growers had not developed networks for obtaining 
information on their export markets pesticide requirements the 
report said 
the gao was asked to look into efforts being made by foreign 
governments and private industries to ensure imported fresh produce 
meets us safety requirements 
the report was requested by reps leon panetta dcalif and 
frank horton rny 
efforts are being made in the current uruguay round of trade 
negotiations under the general agreement on tariffs and trade to 
harmonize food safety and sanitary requirements including 
pesticide residue standards 
the gao said the five countries like the united states have 
not designed their food safety and quality systems to meet the 
import requirements of other countries 
however the report said some of the countries limit the legal 
availability of pesticides that are also not allowed in the united 
states and help to increase the likelihood that exports to the 
united states will not contain residues of those chemicals 
for example the five governments had prohibited or not 
registered from 81 percent to 94 percent of 52 pesticides whose 
registration the environmental protection agency had canceled or 
suspended as of oct 25 1988 including 26 whose registrations had 
been voluntarily canceled by manufacturers the report said 
gao also identified 110 pesticides registered for use in one or 
more of the five countries that do not have epa tolerances 
established for food use in the united states in some cases epa 
may not have evaluated the pesticides or may have denied a us 
tolerance or registration 
registering pesticides that do not have us registrations or 
epa tolerances may be appropriate in a country because of its 
specific pest problems crops and climate because the pesticides 
are suitable for nonfood uses or because exporters need 
alternative pesticides to be legally available to meet their export 
markets differing requirements the gao said 
even so a pesticide permitted in a foreign country could result 
in that countrys produce being refused us entry if residues are 
detected by the food and drug administration the report said 
