<TEXT>
greeks will vote again sunday for the 
third time in a year in hopes of breaking a political deadlock 
that has created compromise governments unable to confront an 
economy in crisis and growing terrorism 
pollsters predict the election will end like those in june and 
november 1989 with no party winning enough seats to control the 
government 
coalitions formed after last years elections took no effective 
action on foreign domestic or economic policy the european 
community has said greece is in danger of bankruptcy and the ec 
will not bail it out because greece violated austerity requirements 
of a 1985 loan 
some greek officials and economists fear the nation may have to 
surrender some of its economic sovereignty and seek help for the 
first time from the international monetary fund 
without a strong government we are heading for economic 
disaster said stelios argyros president of the federation of 
greek industries he said greece needs a government that can make 
the unpopular decisions required 
the political stalemate began after 15 years of stable 
government which followed seven years of military dictatorship 
that ended in 1974 
in june 1989 the conservative new democracy party and 
communists united to oust premier andreas papandreous socialists 
from eight years in power 
a brief coalition of the unlikely allies presided over the 
indictments of papandreou and several of his ministers on 
corruption charges stemming from banking and wiretapping scandals 
no trial dates have been set 
another coalition formed after the november election was unable 
to stem a resurgence of terrorism end labor unrest or resolve the 
problems of rising tensions with turkey and albania rivals of long 
standing 
neither coalition was willing to negotiate a new military bases 
agreement with the united states or answer the us extradition 
request for mohammed rashid a palestinian wanted for the 1982 
bombing of a pan am jetliner that killed one person 
washington later simplified the bases problem by deciding to 
close two of the four 
recent acts of terror have included firebombings by anarchists 
and political killings and bombings by established terror groups 
today at least five bombs exploded in athens and salonica 
ripping through a government building as well as the offices of 
business groups and labor unions police said no injuries were 
reported and that anonymous callers claimed responsibility on 
behalf of two urban guerrilla groups 
november 17th a leftist group claimed responsibility for the 
september murder of conservative lawmaker pavlos bakonvannis 
soninlaw of new democracy leader constantine mitsotakis 
