<TEXT>
a long march 3 rocket will be launched in the 
remote hills of sichuan province sunday to propel china into the 
international satellite market 
the launching of a usmade telecommunications satellite for 
asiasat a hong kongbased consortium is scheduled for the 
southwest china rocket base at xichang 
it will be almost exactly 20 years since the april 24 1970 
launch of chinas first satellite a 380pound device that circled 
the earth once broadcasting the revolutionary song the east is 
red 
since then china has successfully put 26 satellites into space 
and built a reputation for reliability which the government hopes 
will be the basis for a lucrative launching industry 
asiasat chairman wang jun recently said the 120 million project 
will be a major boon to asian communications it will be capable of 
carrying tv and other telecommunications signals to 25 billion 
people in 30 asian countries 
the 2750pound satellite with a lifespan of about 10 years 
will carry 24 transponders burma and two hong kong companies have 
contracted to use the relay transmitters letters of intent have 
been signed with thailand pakistan south korea nepal and other 
asian countries 
great wall industries chinas governmentbacked launching 
company said it has also agreed to launch an arabsat 
communications satellite in late 1991 and put two more usbuilt 
satellites into orbit for an australian firm in 1991 and 1992 
china is also working on a 150 million earth resources 
satellite with brazil and has a joint project with west germany to 
put a communications satellite in orbit in 1992 
setbacks in west europes ariane space program and the backlog 
of space shuttle launches following the 1986 challenger disaster 
have opened the way for china and others such as the soviet union 
seeking entry into the launching service industry 
political turbulence however has nearly grounded the chinese 
program the us congress in 1988 sought to link the export of 
us satellites to ending chinese missile sales to the middle east 
and american contractors have demanded guarantees the chinese will 
not price them out of the market 
the us government in december 1988 after long negotiations 
agreed to grant export licenses for the three hughes aircraft 
satellites to be launched for asiasat and the australian firm 
aussat 
the chinese agreed to strict safeguards for american technology 
a ceiling of nine international launches over a sixyear period and 
prices that would not undercut foreign competitors 
chinas governmentsubsidized service is 30 percent to 50 
percent cheaper than comparable western services american and 
european launchers continue to complain of chinas low prices 
the inaugural launch was nearly scuttled by the military 
crackdown on chinas prodemocracy movement in june us sanctions 
imposed after june included a ban on satellite exports and it was 
only in december that president bush waived the restrictions 
the satellite to be boosted into geostationary orbit 22300 
miles above the equator has made the trip before 
formerly known as westar vi the satellite was misfired into a 
useless orbit during a 1984 space shuttle flight the next year a 
special space shuttle mission retrieved the satellite 
</TEXT>
