chai ling one of the top student leaders of 
last years prodemocracy movement in beijing made a dramatic 
television appearance tuesday to announce her escape to the west 
after 10 months as a fugitive in china 
i am now safe and sound said chai in a near whisper as her 
husband feng congde sat by her side covering his face as he wept 
please put your minds to rest 
frequently pausing to fight tears chai said the road to 
freedom was very difficult very long because of that as i 
reached the last step toward freedom i almost ran out of energy 
i looked up to see this free world to breath the fresh air 
she said 
the dissident couple were on a wanted list of 21 students 
accused by the chinese communist authorities of leading the 
tiananmen square protests last spring the protests ended june 4 in 
a bloody crackdown by troops that left hundreds dead 
china officially labeled the protests a counterrevolutionary 
rebellion and arrested several of the student leaders 
chai who was nominated for the 1990 nobel peace prize by two 
norwegian legislators immediately went underground after the 
suppression and in a taped message smuggled out of china told of 
the military assault on the protesters 
there had been no confirmed word on her whereabouts since 
television broadcasts ltd did not say where the interview was 
taped but two reliable sources said chai arrived in france this 
week after fleeing china 
chai 23 wore a pink shirt and sat at a table with white 
flowers and a candle to commemorate those who died in the 
prodemocracy movement she vowed to continue struggling for her 
beliefs 
near the end of the 10minute tape which appeared to have been 
filmed in an apartment or hotel room she said long live the 
motherland long live democracy eternal glory to the martyrs of 
democracy 
chai was among the three most prominent student leaders of last 
springs demonstrations one leader wuer kaixi fled to the west 
weeks after the crackdown the other wang dan was captured by 
chinese authorities in beijing 
chais surprise appearance in the west comes nearly a year after 
the prodemocracy demonstrations began last april 15 
chinese authorities are concerned about any renewed 
prodemocracy activities authorities sealed off tiananmen square 
on sunday 
chai was one of the few women in the leadership of the 
autonomous student union that led the democracy movement 
