<TEXT>
an annual survey shows a scant increase this 
year in the percentage of american newspaper reporters editors and 
photographers who are members of racial minorities 
the american society of newspaper editors survey made public 
tuesday said members of racial minorities make up 786 percent of 
the newsroom workforce an increase of threetenths of 1 percent 
over last year 
when the asnes annual survey on minority employment started in 
1978 blacks hispanics asians and american indians constituted 
395 percent of the news staffs the figure has risen gradually 
each year 
asne president loren ghiglione editor of the southbridge 
mass news said this years increase actually represented a 
setback since the number of minorities in the overall population 
probably grew at a faster pace 
in these tough economic times perhaps any increase in the 
percentage of people of color should be applauded ghiglione said 
but merv aubespin chairman of the asne minorities committee 
said the slight gain was embarrassing for our industry which 
prides itself on putting the spotlight on the ills of society 
newspapers survival depend on serving a changing 
constituency and minority journalists are essential to that 
effort aubespin said 
asne has adopted a goal of making newsroom staffs equivalent to 
the racial diversity of society as a whole by the year 2000 an 
estimated 16 percent of americans are nonwhite 
an indication that newspapers were trying to close the gap came 
in the surveys finding that 19 percent of entrylevel journalists 
were members of a racial minority last year the figure was 18 
percent 
the survey said minorities make up 46 percent of newsroom 
supervisors 8 percent of copy editors 87 percent of reporters 
and 107 percent of photographers 
all told the nations 1642 dailies employ 4467 members of 
minorities out of a total work force of 56884 
papers with no minority editorial staff members constituted 56 
percent of all dailies in 1987 55 percent in 1988 and 54 percent 
in 1989 and 1990 
most of the newspapers with only whites were smaller papers and 
most were in the midwest where fewer minorities live the survey 
showed they represent only 18 percent of total us newspaper 
circulation 
editors of small papers in parts of the country with few 
minority residents have said they rarely receive applications from 
nonwhites 
nearly half of the participating newspapers agreed to make their 
responses public of those these papers had news staffs of at 
least 20 percent minorities 
