a government study released tuesday said 
20000 australians will die this year from diseases related to 
smoking an increase of more than 10 percent in three years 
tobacco is the leading addictive substance causing death and 
premature mortality in australia said the study by the health 
department of the state of western australia 
the study was released at the opening of the seventh world 
conference on smoking and health it also said 9652 smokers in 
australia will develop cancer this year and that 100000 others 
will be hospitalized with other health problems 
australians will lose 100000 premature years of life from 
smoking in 1990 alone the study said 
federal health minister dr neal blewett among 800 experts from 
70 countries at the conference said 18000 australians died during 
1987 as a direct result of smoking the figure represents 71 
percent of all drugcaused deaths he said 
in a keynote address at the fourday conference blewett said 
lung cancer caused by cigarette smoking is set to overtake breast 
cancer as the most common form of malignancy among australian women 
by the early 1990s 
he said that while lung cancer mortality rates among men had 
fallen over the last 30 years the death rate among women continued 
to rise 
blewett said australia was at the forefront of the battle 
against tobacco which led the labor government of prime minister 
bob hawke to ban smoking in all federal buildings federally 
controlled hospitals and on domestic flights 
