<TEXT>
the us postal service board of governors 
approved spending 3793 million tuesday on new letter sorting 
machines 
the board meeting in raleigh nc voted to launch the program 
that will lead to barcoding of all mail by 1995 
bar codes are a series of thin lines similar to those used in 
supermarket pricing 
the money approved tuesday will cover purchase of 1349 
automatic barcode reading machines which can sort mail carrying 
the codes it is the first of a threephase program to make the 
coding universal 
bar codes already are being used in sorting much business mail 
and the company sending the mail applies the codes in the lower 
corner of the letter 
the new machines will be able to read a code anywhere on the 
face of the letter an advantage which is expected to encourage 
more businesses to use the codes 
individuals will not be expected to place barcodes on their 
mail however by the mid1990s the postal service will begin 
placing the codes on letters that do not have them to allow the 
material to be sorted by machine 
</TEXT>
