<TEXT>
east germanys main political groups agreed 
tuesday to try to form the nations first noncommunist government 
before april 15 and resolve lingering differences over unification 
with west germany 
the conservative alliance for germany winner of the most 
parliament seats in the march 18 elections and closely allied with 
west german chancellor helmut kohl met for formal talks with the 
social democrats who finished second 
party leaders said following the afternoon session they had 
agreed on a framework for talks that they expected would result in 
a governing coalition of this nation of 16 million residents by 
easter sunday april 15 
they agreed too to form smaller groups to discuss the issues 
that divide them particularly the pace of reunification the talks 
are aimed at forging a grand coalition that includes both 
conservatives and liberals 
east germanys disparate political factions had suddenly united 
this week to demand that west germany give 1to1 value to east 
german marks when the nations reunify and the powerful deutsche 
mark becomes the common currency 
unification talks with west germany had been temporarily on hold 
while the newly elected parliament chose a leadership to replace 
the caretaker communist government the caretaker government has 
been running the country since the fall revolution toppled the 
hardline communist regime of erich honecker 
the talks also follow the resignation of the social democrats 
leader ibrahim boehme amid allegations he had links to the hated 
stasi secret police the controversy surrounding boehme had 
hampered negotiations 
social democratic officials met with alliance for germany 
negotiators just hours after the social democrats announced they 
were ready to begin formal talks officials from the tiny free 
democratic party also participated in the meeting 
the alliance for germany is a threeparty coalition that favors 
quick reunification with west germany it received the most votes 
in parliamentary elections march 18 but not enough to form a 
majority in the 400seat parliament 
a twothirds majority is needed to make major decisions for 
rapid unification 
rainer eppelmann leader of democratic awakening one of the 
parties in the alliance for germany said he was hoping for a quick 
agreement so people in east germany know where they stand 
the social democrats and the alliance have already held 
exploratory talks about forming a government but progress was 
hindered by the social democrats insistence that one of the three 
parties within the alliance the ultraconservative german social 
union be excluded from any government 
the social democrats have now dropped that demand but they are 
seeking to limit any cabinet posts the german social union would 
have in a government 
the third party in the alliance is the christian demcratic union 
meckel said a key reason for the social democrats decision to 
enter formal coalition talks is the dispute over introducing west 
germanys mark as east germanys currency 
west germanys central bank has insisted most east german marks 
be exchanged at a 2to1 ratio that has angered many east germans 
who were expecting to benefit from a 1to1 exchange rate 
lothar de maiziere head of the alliance for germany said 
monday he was disappointed with the west german proposal and made 
clear he favors a 1to1 conversion rate 
meckel said de maizieres stand leads social democratic 
officials to believe the two sides could be successful in coalition 
negotiations 
for the first time i have seen that mr de maiziere has 
publicly said something which is seen differently in bonn we see 
this as a sign of hope meckel said 
the social democrats have previously complained that the 
alliance for germany is letting the west german government call too 
many of the shots in drafting plans for german unification 
nonetheless negotiations between the two sides could be tricky 
because the social democrats have opted for a slower pace to german 
unity than the alliance for germany 
