<TEXT>
the house public works and transportation 
committee voted 355 tuesday to approve legislation to protect the 
civil rights of millions of disabled americans including those 
infected with the aids virus 
the committee vote is the third out of four needed to bring the 
americans with disabilities act to the house floor the senate 
passed the bill last september by a 768 vote 
the house judiciary committee the final committee is expected 
to take up the bill near the end of this month and a vote by the 
full house could occur in may 
the bill protects disabled people from job discrimination it 
guarantees equal access to public and private transportation as 
well as stores restaurants business and professional services 
the hearing and speechimpaired would be guaranteed access to 
special telephone services 
backers say the law is carefully constructed to avoid undue 
hardships on businesses they say it provides lenient timetables 
for implementation 
critics say the bill is too vague for the ordinary 
businessperson to understand leaving interpretation of the law up 
to activists and judges they also say the bill provides nothing to 
offset the high cost to businesses 
the two previous house committees education and labor and 
energy and commerce also passed the bill by similarly large 
margins 
although the bill does protect people with the aids virus 
against discrimination it does not protect homosexuals and 
bisexuals against discrimination it protects former but not 
current drug users 
aids is known to be spread by certain homosexual contact 
contaminated hypodermic needles and transfusions of infected blood 
a woman who is infected during pregnancy passes the disease to her 
infant 
president bush referred last week to the bill in a speech in 
which he urged congress to get on with the job of passing a law 
to protect people with the virus or with the disease 
bush did not mention however the conflict between the 
administration and congressional supporters over an effort by the 
justice department to change important language dealing with 
employment provisions of the law 
the administration wants to decouple the disabilities bill from 
the 1964 civil rights act the reason is that civil rights 
advocates have introduced an update of the civil rights act that 
would enable people who are intentionally discriminated against to 
sue employers for damages the administration opposes that change 
title vii of the civil rights act which is referred to in the 
disabilities bill currently limits relief to nondamage remedies 
such as back pay and injunctive relief 
</TEXT>
