the navy wants to know whether ship 
electronics can survive a nuclear explosion in space and has 
decided a simulator test in the gulf of mexico would have no 
significant impact on the environment 
but the service said one of three alternative sites in the gulf 
has too much air and sea traffic to be appropriate for the tests of 
the electromagnetic pulse radiation environment simulator for ships 
empress ii program 
in a draft environmental impact statement the navy this week 
said the two sites it deemed acceptable both are located southeast 
of mobile ala the unacceptable site is located southwest of 
mobile about 40 nautical miles from the coast 
empress ii is a bargemounted pulser that can simulate the 
electromagnetic field that would be generated on earth by a nuclear 
blast in space the system sends out an electromagnetic pulse emp 
that lasts just 10 billionths of a second but measures 50000 
volts per meter at 100 meters from the barge in all directions 
the navy plans to fire the emp at passing ships to test the 
effectiveness of measures designed to protect electronics systems 
from the emp that would result from a nuclear explosion in space 
critics of the program contend that the emp would endanger 
marine and plant life in the gulf the navy personnel aboard the 
test ship and the electronic systems of airplanes and ships that 
might be in the area 
but in the draft study on the program the navy concluded that no 
such dangers exist 
the collective potential environmental impact of the proposed 
empress ii action is estimated to be minor the navy said 
within this minor category the potential impact is greater on 
the socioeconomic issues and less on both the natural resources and 
the physical site itself 
ships would be barred from passing within two nautical miles of 
