<TEXT>
five midwestern senators introduced 
legislation tuesday to include in the 1990 farm bill that they said 
would protect farmers against the rising costs of growing food 
meanwhile a house agriculture subcommittee approved a dairy 
program for the farm bill that revamps price supports in order to 
stop excessive production of butter fat 
the senate bill dubbed the farm income and flexibility act 
will be the basis for the target price section of the massive 
legislation congress writes every five years to set agriculture 
policy said the group of democratic senators 
the legislation is necessary to preserve family farming which 
is the best protection against rising consumer food costs that the 
government can devise said the senators the group includes sens 
robert kerrey and james exon of nebraska tom daschle of south 
dakota tom harkin of iowa and kent conrad of north dakota 
kerrey said the legislation would cost about 12 billion 
annually the bush administration wants to lower the cost of target 
prices and has recommended spending no more than about 10 billion 
next year 
target prices are the amounts the government sets for wheat 
corn cotton soybeans and rice if the market price does not reach 
the amount the government pays the farmer the difference 
under the house dairy program the government would buy up to 7 
billion pounds of milk products at 1060 per hundred pounds if 
they cant be sold on the open market farmers who produce more 
than their share of the governments limit would get a lower amount 
the senate has not approved a dairy plan yet 
kerrey who has led the battle against the administrations 
target price proposals said there are three basic reasons why 
consumers should want the government involved in the farm business 
government management of surpluses protects against unstable 
weather conditions 
us food prices are kept the lowest in the world by a strong 
government program 
the subsidy is a bargain at less than the 1 percent of the 
annual federal budget 
people who live in urban areas have an interest in seeing the 
family farm preserved as a guard against the higher food prices 
likely if farms were consolidated said an aide to daschle 
if agricultural production were in the hands of just a few 
people food prices would also be under their control said mark 
ulven 
if farmers dont have the governments help in covering their 
production costs they might easily go out of business and sell 
their farms to a corporation he said 
us consumers today spend just 104 percent of their 
disposable income on food the lowest level in history and less 
than consumers in any other country said kerrey 
but the producers share of each dollar spent on food has 
dropped to an alltime low he said 
in 1988 according to usda farmers and ranchers received only 
30 cents of each dollar spent on food consumed at home kerrey 
said 
conrad said that once inflation was taken into account net farm 
income in the 1980s was the lowest its been since 1910 when the 
government started keeping records 
we keep hearing from the administration that the farm crisis 
is over and farm income is at record levels said conrad 
thats just a bunch of washington happy talk 
provisions in the senators bill include 
tying target prices to increased production costs 
raising loan rates which help determine market prices by more 
than 20 percent next year and setting a floor on the loan rate for 
corn of 210 and for wheat of 275 
establishing a normal crop acreage base for each farm that is 
the total of the farms current cropspecific bases plus the 
average acreage planted to soybeans during the last five years 
raising income support levels on oilseeds oats and barley to 
levels comparable with wheat and corn 
