<TEXT>
last years swirl of political change not only 
raised eastern european nations from oppression but also released 
liberating currents elsewhere this is the last story in a 
fivepart easter series resurrection of nations 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in opera square in timisoara romania people these afternoons 
place lighted candles before wreaths and wooden portraits of jesus 
then kneel to pray in sorrow for those who died there in hope 
for the future of their nation 
that country where nicolae ceausescu had vowed communism would 
never budge not until pears grow on poplar trees broke free 
in one spontaneous instant when the despot was jeered in public 
forced to flee and four days later executed by a firing squad 
the upheaval which began with a lone pastor in timisoara was 
both tame in origins yet wild unplanned and headlong murderously 
repulsed yet successful fervently keen yet stained with vindictive 
passion a maelstrom producing a democracy 
the events were surprising fantastic and dreadful all at 
the same time the rev wolfgang hermann rehner a romanian 
lutheran pastor told a clergy meeting 
it was the resurrection of a trampled prostrate people an 
easterhued rising from despair 
the romanian orthodox church after its collaborationist leaders 
had resigned said in a message to the worlds christians 
after decades of slavery under the communist dictatorship and 
after immense suffering god has turned his eyes toward our 
people he has raised us from the shadow of death and set us 
free 
romanias rocky stampede to liberty began in middecember in 
timisoara where the softspoken but courageous rev laszlo tokes 
37 had been threatened his church and home raided for 
criticizing the regime he sent his pregnant wife and young son to 
live with relatives 
on dec 15 tokes was served with a courtordered eviction 
notice backed up by his subservient protestant reformed bishop to 
keep their pastor his congregation ringed the church 
by dusk of the next day the crowd had grown to 5000 by then 
they were surrounded by the detested security police the 
securitate armed with automatic weapons and small tanks 
we want liberty down with ceausescu the crowd chanted the 
securitate responded with bullets and the first victims fell 
but the crowds returned the next day they numbered 50000 in 
the city center dec 17 most of the killing in timisoara occurred 
that day amid repeated bursts of gunfire and tear gas screams and 
falling bodies punctuated the chaos 
demonstrations quickly flared in other cities and met similar 
reprisals in timisoara slayings continued dec 18 thirty 
youngsters were reportedly mowed down as they stood with candles on 
the cathedral steps 
figures revised from much higher early estimates indicate about 
100 died in timisoara and more than 300 were wounded 
officers of the regular army a secondclass outfit given low 
pay and shoddy equipment refused to join the elite securitate in 
the slaughter 
as demonstrations spread to arad sibiu and other towns 
including the capital of bucharest the securitate kept up the 
killing firing from buildings running cars and from atop armored 
personnel carriers raising the toll to 746 dead 
the solidarity demonstration for me changed into a general 
protest against the regime tokes said later 
on dec 21 ceausescu staged a rally outside party headquarters 
the ornate former palace of the romanian monarch workers and party 
functionaries were herded into palace square with placards hailing 
ceausescu 
in a raspy voice the 71yearold dictator railed against 
foreign enemies and terrorist subversives suddenly from 
far back boos sounded like a wave boos and jeers rolled up to 
the balcony 
ceausescu froze and fear crossed his face just before he 
ordered the television cameras cut off when the army refused to 
shoot he and his despised wife elena fled first in a 
helicopter then in a red car 
captured dec 22 in a grain silo the ceausescus were given a 
twohour trial and shot on christmas day 
tokes kept on the run all that tumultuous week became a member 
of the unity council of the provisional government the national 
salvation front it outlawed the feared securitate and set 
multiparty elections for may 20 
among celebrating crowds a continual chant memorialized the 
events and the city that started it all timisoara timisoara 
for the first time in decades full romanian orthodox liturgies 
appeared on television along with special services for those who 
died 
tokes later was named bishop replacing the collaborating 
prelate who had sought his ouster 
but the falls of ceausescu brought new chaos and failed to 
banish old anxieties romanians have no experience with democracy 
and the front is constantly challenged and secondguessed 
hardships and scarcities remain scars of past horrors and 
suspicions in a country long thick with informers and mincuini 
the lies that characterized the past regime 
arduous reconstruction lies ahead in the liberated countries 
including the latest one mongolia in that land of herdsmen 
between the soviet and china the communist party on march 14 
surrendered its constitutional monopoly and prepared for multiparty 
elections later this year 
besides the dismemberment of communism liberating currents also 
stirred in latin america and south africa 
in nicaragua voters on feb 26 ousted marxistleaning daniel 
ortega the new president violeta barrios de chamorro assumes 
office april 25 
in haiti former supreme court justice ertha pascal trouillot 
last month became the first civilian president since dictator 
jeanclaude baby doc duvalier was toppled in 1986 ending 29 
years of duvalier dictatorship 
in chile patricio aylwins election victory dec 14 made him 
the first civilian president since 1973 the 17year rule of gen 
augusto pinochet had been marked by torture political killings and 
disappearances 
in brazil the first popularly elected president in 29 years 
fernando collor de mello assumed office march 15 
in namibia independence was achieved march 21 after 75 years of 
military rule by bordering south africa 
in south africa president fw de klerk in february lifted a 
30year ban on the african national congress which has fought 
minority white rule and released its leader nelson mandela from 
27 years in prison 
hallelujah hallelujah cried south africas anglican 
archbishop desmond tutu who did a little dance freedom is 
coming 
theres no single explanation for it all said monsignor 
john tracy ellis a noted us catholic historian its a 
univeral phenomenon of the human spirit that longs to be free 
freedom is in the air and please god that it will sweep the 
whole planet and embrace the poor people of cambodia and china and 
north korea 
in the daybreak of change many horizons remain clouded but glow 
with promise 
you will know the truth jesus said of his crucifixion and 
resurrection and the truth will make you free 
</TEXT>
