<TEXT>
graham marshall in his middle years appears to have an enviable 
life important post at a manhattan ad agency wife and home in the 
suburbs 
but on closer examination we see that his job is threatened by a 
younger ruthless executive his wife is a nagging shrew and he is 
drowning in debt 
then one day in the subway a tragedy makes graham realize that 
crimes can go undetected he cooly plans complicated schemes to rid 
himself of his enemies his plot is triggered when he loses a 
muchneeded promotion to the young conniver causing his wifes 
comment i forgive you for your failure 
a shock to the system a wordplay on grahams mode of 
execution might have been minorleague hitchcock but the movie 
bears watching if only to observe a master performer at work 
michael caine is graham marshall and it is a pleasure to see a 
real pro make more of a script than what is on the pages caines 
bland face reflects all the maddening frustrations that drive him 
toward his devilish deeds when he rages against the yuppie who 
usurped his job caine is olympian in his wrath when he cooly 
executes his remotecontrol murders he is as menacing as freddy 
kreuger 
a shock to the system marks a promising entry into feature 
films for jan egleson who has directed prestige films for public 
television he skillfully plays the murderous events against the 
normality of new york high rises and peaceful suburbia 
andrew klavan wrote the script adapting simon bretts novel 
the plot is cleverly devised but its hard to believe that caines 
acts would not attract more police suspicion his only pursuer is a 
suburban detective will patton who seems slow to round up a case 
the film is well cast elizabeth mcgovern is convincingly 
vulnerable as the coworker who becomes caines lover and potential 
victim peter riegert the pickle salesman in crossing delancy 
is ideal as the upwardly mobile ad man john mcmartin has strong 
moments as the executive whose life burns out when he is forced 
into early retirement swoosie kurtz offers a convincing argument 
for uxoricide 
a shock to the system a corsair production release is 
rated r for language and adult material running time 87 minutes 
</TEXT>
