<TEXT>
the chairman of the securities and exchange 
commission criticized proposed changes in state takeover laws like 
those being considered in pennsylvania saying they seek to tilt 
the balance against shareholders 
significant efforts are underway at the state level to shield 
management from shareholder oversight richard c breeden told 
the council of institutional investors a group of pension fund 
managers on monday 
pennsylvania indiana and other states recently have sought to 
tilt the balance of corporate power in favor of corporate 
management and against shareholders by insulating decisions by 
boards of directors from effective review either by the judiciary 
or shareholders he added 
although most proposed legislation is not in its final form 
the us supreme court has indicated clearly that states do have 
the ability to legislate in takeover areas said randall 
schumann a spokesman for the north american securities 
administrators association a nationwide organization of state 
level securities regulators 
supporters of the pending pennsylvania legislation have hailed 
it as the nations toughest antitakeover sanction but critics 
warn it could discourage longterm investment because corporate 
officers would be less accountable for their actions 
breeden said federal regulators were concerned about state 
legislation that would insulate managers and boards from 
shareholders and thus possibly cause institutional investors to 
shift muchneeded capital from securities like stocks to those 
based on debt like junk bonds 
that would make it tougher for us businesses to raise large 
sums of money for longrange goals like plant expansion research 
and development 
who wants to be a longterm captive investor breeden asked 
rhetorically 
the legislation passed by the pennsylvania senate and awaiting 
action in the house would make it more difficult for corporate 
raiders to take over a pennsylvania company or extract 
greenmail abovemarket prices paid by management to buy back 
the companys stock from wouldbe raiders 
the bill also would give corporate boards far more discretion 
than they have now to consider interests other than those of the 
shareholders in making decisions about takeover bids 
breeden said shareholder input in running a company is 
guaranteed under federal law and while we respect states 
rights in matters of corporate governance we will not hesitate 
to seek to enforce federal interests 
breed also said the sec was reviewing the shareholder voting and 
proxy process especially changes recommended by the california 
public employees retirement system and a shareholders rights 
group the united shareholders association a proxy is a 
shareholders absentee ballot for a companys annual meeting 
