<TEXT>
prices on the tokyo stock exchange rose sharply 
today in nervous rollercoaster trading and the dollar dropped 
against the japanese yen 
the 225issue nikkei stock average gained a hefty 75765 points 
or 27 percent ending the day at 2875765 in morning trading 
the index first rose more than 500 points then fell below the 
28000point line 
the index rose again in the afternoon as participants decided 
the market had bottomed out in the morning said yoshiro inoue an 
analyst with nomura securities co 
he said market players expect the index will stay above the 
27200point level 30 percent below where it stood at the end of 
last year 
inoue said another encouraging sign was the stability of 
government bond prices which remained relatively steady despite 
mondays heavy losses in the stock market 
in currency dealings the dollar closed at 15895 yen down 100 
yen from mondays close of 15995 yen the us currency opened at 
15910 yen and ranged between 15880 yen and 15935 yen 
on monday as the dollar surged to a threeyear high against the 
japanese yen the nikkei index plunged 197838 points or 659 
percent to close at 2800207 in its secondlargest singleday 
decline ever the plunge followed a 104571point or 337 
percent fall in the index last friday 
analysts said both currency and stock markets were shaken monday 
by a report in a leading japanese financial newspaper that major 
life insurers planned to shift funds out of the stock market 
volume on the markets first section today was estimated at 650 
million shares up from 450 million shares on monday 
the price of benchmark no 119 japanese government bonds closed 
at 8644 points up from mondays close at 8602 their yield fell 
to 7260 percent from the previous days 7350 percent 
but inoue said uncertainty remained in the market the index 
has only entered a range that everybody predicted would be the 
markets bottom but there may be further shakeups inoue said 
other traders said it would take time for the market to regain 
its energy and make a stable recovery 
as long as the government differentiates between interest 
rates and the foreign exchange rate and takes two different 
approaches both markets will stabilize and will help the stock 
market recover inoue said 
he said it would not be wise to raise interest rates in order to 
support the yen 
on march 25 the bank of japan raised its official discount rate 
by 1 percentage point to 525 percent in a move widely seen as an 
attempt to bolster the value of the dropping yen 
dealers said the finance ministry on monday bought about 1 
trillion yen 63 billion in government bonds to support their 
price and prevent yields from rising excessively 
meanwhile bank of japan governor yasushi mieno said today the 
decline in japanese stock prices since the beginning of this year 
has been excessive 
the nikkei index has lost more than 10000 points or 26 
percent so far this year 
traders said currency market participants focused on the stock 
market performance in the absence of other marketaffecting news 
toru kanai a foreign exchange analyst with new japan securities 
co said the yen fell in the morning session as stock prices 
fell but the afternoon rebound in share prices did not boost 
yenbuying incentives 
kanai said market players avoided major moves before the meeting 
among finance ministers from the group of seven industrialized 
nations scheduled for april 7 and the conclusion of ongoing 
usjapan trade talks in washington 
but kanai said the dollar was likely to continue to rise because 
market demand for the us currency remained strong and there was 
little incentive to buy the yen 
he said that after the trade talks and the g7 meetingthe 
dollar will jump over the 160yen level and rise further 
finance minister ryutaro hashimoto said today he was concerned 
by recent exchange rate movements and hoped stability would return 
to the market soon 
