<TEXT>
the governments chief economic forecasting 
gauge fell 10 percent in february the commerce department 
reported today but analysts said it would have changed little 
except for a drop in building permits 
the index of leading economic indicators designed to forecast 
economic activity six to nine months in advance had risen the 
previous three months 
but because of the unusual circumstances surrounding the indexs 
building permit component many analysts expressed skepticism in 
advance of the february report 
the analysts said todays index would be lowered by the february 
drop from the unusually large number of permits builders sought in 
january to take advantage of record warm weather and to beat a 
deadline for meeting expensive new building standards 
the standards required by 1989 fair housing legislation are 
designed to make apartment buildings more accessible to the 
handicapped the national association of home builders said the 
standards would add between 3600 and 7200 to the cost of an 
apartment 
according to a survey of 51 top economists published in blue 
chip economic indicators the gross national product the nations 
output of goods and services will grow 17 percent in 1990 
but the survey by eggert economic enterprises of sedona ariz 
says the economic outlook remains the most sluggish since the 
recession year of 1982 
seven of the 11 forwardlooking statistics contributed to the 
decline led by the steep fall in building permits in february 
after a sharp jump in the previous month the warmest january on 
record 
other negatives included faster business delivery times lower 
stock prices a decline in plant and equipment orders a decrease 
in the price of raw materials a decline in the backlog of 
manufacturers unfilled orders and a drop in an index measuring 
consumer confidence 
three of the components were positive including an increase in 
orders for consumer goods a gain in the money supply and a drop in 
weekly unemploylment claims 
one indicator the length of the average workweek was unchanged 
the various changes left the index at 1440 percent of its 1982 
base of 100 the index fell 06 percent from september through 
february after declining 05 percent the previous six months 
the january index was revised from unchanged to a 02 percent 
gain because of an increase in new orders for consumer goods 
the december index was revised down from 06 percent to 04 
percent because of a shorter workweek the november index had risen 
01 percent 
the analysts said because so many building permits were issued 
in january there were fewer issued in february causing the number 
to decline a sharp 25 percent economist michael p niemira of 
mitsubishi bank in new york said that drove the overall index down 
if that onetime aberration were not included the index might 
have exceeded its january level niemira said 
michael k evans head of a forecasting organization here wrote 
in the evans report shortly before the index was released that 
except for that one anomaly the index would be up slightly 
excluding the housing permits component the index is expected 
to stand unchanged signifying continuation of restrained economic 
growth samuel d kahan chief economist for fuji securities inc 
of chicago wrote in his organizations weekly perspectives last 
week 
david berson chief economist for the federal national mortgage 
association characterized the economy so far this year as a 
quarter of recovery 
we recovered from the very cold december berson explained 
we recovered from the boeing strike we recovered from the san 
francisco bay area earthquake and the hurricane hugo all of 
which helped depress the fourth quarter 
</TEXT>
