<TEXT>
pork ribs for backyard barbecues are costing 
more this spring along with just about everything else thats part 
of a hog 
the agriculture department says hog farmers may increase 
production seasonally later this year but that wont do much to 
cool off prices before this fall 
kevin bost of the departments economic research service said 
last fridays report showing further declines in the us inventory 
of hogs and pigs confirmed our expectations for reduced supplies 
this spring and summer 
as a result he said we should be looking at higher wholesale 
pork prices and higher retail prices in the next few months 
the departments allcut pork price a weighted blend of prices 
paid by consumers at retail stores rose to 197 per pound in 
february bost said monday in a telephone interview that matched 
the alltime high set in the late summer of 1987 
bost said wholesale pork prices have continued to edge higher 
meaning that i wouldnt be surprised to see a new record high 
retail price in march when the labor department releases those 
consumer figures on april 17 
in another report last friday the usda showed the march 
hogcorn feed price ratio at a relatively high 222 bushels up 
from 208 in february and 151 in march 1989 
those numbers represent the bushels of corn equal in value to 
100 pounds of live hog shipped to market other factors are also 
important in the hog business but feed costs are a major item for 
producers thinking about expanding or cutting back their operations 
roughly the higher the number in the hogcorn ratio the 
greater the opportunity for profit 
in general returns to hog producers have been pretty 
favorable since the middle part of last year bost said if 
prices go on good enough for long enough eventually they 
expand 
one question is the corn crop and whether livestock producers 
have ample feed supplies at reasonable prices bost said recent 
moisture conditions sure doesnt hurt those prospects for the 
1990 harvest 
based on the situation as it looks now pork production probably 
will begin to pick up at least seasonally this fall 
were probably looking at larger pork supplies in 1991 bost 
said 
meanwhile bost and his usda colleagues say consumers may see 
some easing of beef prices this summer according to the april 
issue of agricultural outlook magazine but it wont be dramatic 
improved prospects for spring grazing in some areas probably 
will increase retention of females for cattle herd expansion and 
lower slaughter of beef cows and heifers the report said 
as that happens there will be less nonfed beef for 
consumers which affects hamburger prices 
prices of choicegrade fed steers moving to slaughter will 
continue to decline as marketready supplies increase into early 
summer the report said in some markets prices may fall below 
70 per hundredweight perhaps not reaching the mid70s again 
until fall 
at retail choicegrade beef rose to a record level in january 
of 2813 per pound on an allcut basis and edged still higher to 
2815 in february the report said 
broiler prices have been supported by the strength in beef and 
pork with retail prices in the first quarter averaging about the 
same as a year ago despite a production increase of about 8 percent 
from yearearlier levels further increases are expected 
in march the estimated 12city wholesale broiler price was 
about 61 cents per pound up from 5737 cents in february and 517 
cents in january in march 1989 the 12city average was 621 cents 
the wholesale broiler prices in 1990 may average 5157 cents 
per pound compared with 59 for last year the report said 
</TEXT>
