<DOCNO> AP900403-0238 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
general motors corp president and chief 
operating officer robert c stempel who rose through the 
production ranks of the worlds largest automaker was named today 
to succeed the retiring roger b smith as chairman 
smith who officially steps down july 31 at age 65 announced 
stempels selection at a news conference at gm headquarters 
lloyd e reuss a gm executive vice president will succeed 
stempel as president smith said the position of chief operating 
officer also held by stempel was being eliminated 
stempel told reporters at the news conference his first priority 
is increasing gm sales 
one of our major ones challenges is to increase our 
north american market share profitably stempel said there is 
no higher priority in general motors than increasing our market 
share profitably 
gms share of the north american car and truck market has 
dropped to 346 percent last year from 441 percent in 1980 
gms board of directors met monday at the companys sprawling 
car and truckmaking complex in oshawa ontario 
a team of outside directors has been serving as a search 
committee for the chairman of the company that last year made 422 
billion on revenue of 1269 billion 
smith who said he would remain on gms board praised stempel 
for his domestic and international experience 
im leaving general motors on august 1 convinced weve got 
probably the greatest team weve ever had because weve got some 
of the greatest challenges weve ever had the outgoing chairman 
said 
most speculation in recent months has centered on the 
56yearold stempel although the names of two gm executive vice 
presidents f alan smith and john f smith jr also have been 
mentioned as candidates for chairman both smiths no relation to 
roger smith had financial backgrounds 
stempel began his gm career as a senior detailer in the chassis 
design department of the companys oldsmobile division in 1958 
he became general manager of the companys pontiac division in 
1978 and two years later went to europe to head gms adam opel ag 
carmaking operation in west germany 
in 1982 stempel returned to the united states to head the 
chevrolet division and in 1984 was named executive in charge of the 
buickoldsmobilecadillac group 
in february 1986 stempel joined gms board of directors as 
executive vice president in charge of the worldwide truck amp bus 
group and the overseas group 
the following year he became gms president 
reuss 53 has been executive vice president in charge of north 
american passenger car groups and a board member since february 
1986 he was given the additional responsibility of gms truck and 
bus grup in 1987 he started as a gm engineer in 1959 
gm is the second of the big three us automakers to revamp its 
top management for the 1990s 
on march 1 harold poling became ford motor cos chairman 
succeeding donald petersen poling will hold the top job at ford 
for three years before he is expected to give way to allan gilmour 
executive vice president 
chrysler corp chairman lee iacoccas contract with the nations 
no 3 automaker expires late next year 
gm has been wrestling with excess plant capacity as the us 
auto market softens the huge automaker is expected to shutter its 
lakewood car assembly plant in atlanta this summer and half of its 
lordstown ohio plant next year 
since 1987 gm has shut down assembly plants in framingham 
mass kansas city mo and pontiac mich 
balancing plant capacity with a shrinking car and truck market 
is one of the big challenges facing the new gm chairman 
others include managing the launch and growth of gms saturn 
corp which plans to begin making a small importfighting car 
this summer in spring hill tenn and contract negotiations with 
the united auto workers union which has tapped job security as its 
top bargaining priority 
the saturn project originally proposed in 1983 as a 5billion 
program to build 500000 subcompacts a year has been cut nearly in 
half yet with its unique labor agreement and manufacturing 
techniques it is viewed as a laboratory of things to come at gm 
and a key step in the automakers attempt to arrest a decline in 
its market share 
smith repeatedly has vowed to drive the first production car off 
the assembly line now scheduled for about a month before his 
retirement 
but overshadowing all the new product projects are gms labor 
relations with the uaw since the last threeyear contract was 
