<TEXT>
the first commercially available optical disc 
recorder that can erase stored images and record over them will 
give broadcasters a better tool than videotape for showing video 
replays panasonic said 
the new device would allow television stations to more easily 
replay a sports highlight for example than conventional videotape 
technology the japanese company said monday it also can store 
more minutes of video and provides better picture quality than 
videotape 
the recorder can find an individual frame of recorded video 
within one second the company said thats much quicker than 
videotape machines in which the tape must be rewound to the exact 
spot 
panasonic also said the machine could be used for interactive 
training programs to store criminal records in police departments 
and for sales and marketing uses such as recording videotapes of 
homes to show to prospective buyers 
eventually similar devices could be made for home use said 
edward rothchild a san franciscobased consultant on optical 
storage devices he calls such recordable laser video disc players 
the next mass consumer products which could supplant vcrs and 
videotapes much as compact discs are replacing phonograph records 
the current generation of home laser video disc machines can 
only play prerecorded discs they have failed to become a major 
market in part because they cannot record tv shows 
optical storage devices have been around for years but most of 
them cannot be erased once the original recording is made they are 
used primarily for longterm storage of computer data such as 
invoices or bank statements 
panasonics device works on the magnetooptical principal in 
which a magnetic field is used to magnetize certain portions of the 
optical disc a laser beam reads these magnetized portions and 
converts them into a picture unlike a compact disc it stores the 
information in conventional analog form instead of in the computer 
language of digital storage 
jay bretzmann an analyst for international data corp said the 
devices major advantage over videotape is its ease of locating 
certain portions of stored video he also said it could be reused 
many more times than videotape which tends to degrade in quality 
over time 
i think it will expand the market for these devices he said 
he said panasonic is leveraging the expertise of its parent 
matsushita electric industrial co of japan in optical storage 
devices 
rothchild said other japanese companies have demonstrated 
similar machines but that panasonic is the first to the market 
in addition to their appeal to tv stations he said they also 
should prove popular with movie studios which already are using 
nonerasable optical discs to edit film erasable discs would be a 
great costsavings he said 
panasonic did not disclose the price of the recorder it plans 
to begin shipments in the fourth quarter 
</TEXT>
