<TEXT>
if dealmaking really is art then the bidding 
for bonwit teller was the aesthetic equivalent of finger painting 
a bankruptcy court hearing monday turned into a corporate casbah 
as attorneys frantically arranged offers for the failed department 
store chain not over the typical wall street power lunch but 
within earshot of a federal judge 
deals came together fell apart and came together again bidders 
changed sides a dramatic 11thhour proposal by a wouldbe savior 
failed a lawyer played auctioneer as two sides upped offers 1 
million at a pop waiting for the opposition to crumble 
i need 250 thousand from each of you and i need it now 
implored donald n david a lawyer representing dealmaster donald 
trump to members of a group bidding on five of the 16 bonwit 
department stores 
david got an icy stare from one participant who refused to 
raise his ante a representative of trump whose eponymous gold 
tower on fifth avenue houses bonwits flagship store and two 
other groups contributed the difference the deal lived 
bankruptcy court is becoming a home away from home for american 
big business in the 1990s as companies stumble under the weight of 
junk bonds and other takeover and expasionrelated problems in the 
1980s the decade of debt a new era of restructuring means more 
unusual proceedings like the one monday in which about 200 people 
mostly lawyers crammed into a steamy bankruptcy courtroom 
overlooking new york harbor 
amid shouting cajoling the toot of the staten island ferry and 
pounding of a jackhammer six floors below bonwits was carved into 
pieces lawyers constantly pleaded for another minute as they 
huddled to cut a deal 
most unusual was that the nearly 10hour ordeal took place in 
open court where judges rarely tolerate more than one person 
speaking at a time always deferentially let alone protests and 
open outcry bidding 
ive never seen anything like it before david of the new 
york firm dreyer amp traub said tuesday i think if it werent for 
that informality they wouldnt have raised anywhere near the amount 
of money they did for the estate 
lj hooker corp bonwits atlantabased parent held the 
auction to boost the liquidation value of the upscale store chain 
it bought three years ago hooker had received just one bid for 
five stores prior to the auction 
on monday the take for hooker creditors rose by millions also 
some of the stores may survive 
a first round of bidding included offers from a french retailer 
a florida department store a buffalo chain a canadian investor 
and a group that included trump and the womens apparel store the 
limited 
as the second round began the trump group booted the limited 
and embraced pyramid cos a syracuse nybased shopping mall 
developer and owner that already had made the preauction 
fivestore bid 
when it became apparent the group needed to raise its 2025 
million offer or lose out to a possible combination of other bids 
the haggling intensified david an energetic bearded man with a 
thick new york accent hustled about a station of about 15 lawyers 
and businessmen seeking more money 
he got it in 20 minutes the bid rose by 15 million 
collapsing once in the process 
meantime the court looked more like sothebys when two bidders 
battled for a bonwit store in exclusive palm beach fla lawyers 
for frances brewster inc a florida retailer and ralph hibbard a 
canadian investor called bids from opposite sides of the 
courtroom raising the price to 22 million from 16 million 
sounds like an auction bankruptcy judge tina brozman said 
to laughter 
after the hibbard group conceded hooker lawyer sheldon hirshon 
serving as impromptu auctioneer said going once going 
twice 
the final drama was provided by the days hopedfor white 
knight hooker lawyers had wanted to preserve the bonwits chain 
in the morning they announced that a group led by bonwits exceo 
william ruben was planning a bid for 13 stores in the 
midafternoon they said the deal was off 
around 630 pm lawyers told the judge it was on again ruben 
showed up in court and told reporters his 36 million bid could 
make bonwit viable again all he needed was one day to arrange 
financing 
furious david said reopening the bidding would violate an 
agreement and make a fool out of everybody here hooker 
attorneys eventually acquiesced fearing they could lose all bids 
if the ruben group collapsed 
attorney alan hyman said hooker decided to resort to the heady 
and cerebral theory that a bird in the hand was worth two in the 
bush david an hour after pacing angrily and saying its 
off gave associates two thumbs up 
 
