<TEXT>
opec nations held oil production steady 
in march but remained more than a million barrels a day above their 
selfimposed supply cap according to estimates released tuesday 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries pumped a total 
of about 237 million barrels a day in march the same as in the 
previous month according to the parisbased international energy 
agency 
sales of opec crude oil in march were believed to be lower than 
production due to apparent excess supply of heavy sour grades and 
weaker than expected demand from refiners the group stated 
private analysts predicted the cartel would increase output even 
more this month 
it seems it will go up in april maybe to as much as 24 
million barrels a day said pierre terzian editor of the 
parisbased newsletter petrostrategies 
leading the surge in last months production were saudi arabia 
kuwait the united arab emirates and nigeria according to the 
international energy agencys monthly oil market report all were 
estimated to be above the individual quotas the cartel set for each 
country last year and reaffirmed at a recent meeting in vienna 
the organization imposed a cartelwide ceiling of 221 million 
barrels a day for production in the first half of 1990 to help 
support a price of 18 a barrel but members led by kuwait and the 
united arab emirates have been cheating on their quotas 
oil prices soared in early january but have been gradually 
slipping since then falling in early march below 18 
the average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by the 
agency was 1733 a barrel in the last week of march down from 
1747 the previous week 
prices of west texas intermediate the key american grade have 
ranged from 20 to 22 a barrel during that time 
in an effort to keep prices firm opec oil ministers met last 
month and issued a fresh call for restraint by all nations in the 
normally weak apriljune quarter 
analysts say that if the cartel keeps production high prices 
will weaken in the coming months 
demand for crude normally slumps in the second quarter when 
spring weather warms the united states and other consuming nations 
the international energy agency predicted demand for opec oil at 
204 million barrels a day in the current quarter 
analysts argue that some of the producers particularly kuwait 
want prices to stay at the 18 level so the cartel does not lose 
market share to other oilproducing nations high prices will 
prompt other suppliers to pump more 
according to the oil market report saudi arabia the worlds 
no 1 oil exporter pumped 56 million barrels a day in march 
above its quota of 54 million barrels 
iran and iraq were about at their quotas of 31 million barrels 
a day 
the united arab emirates produced some 2 million barrels a day 
about double its supply cap kuwaits output was estimated at 18 
million barrels a day above its limit of 15 million barrels 
nigeria supplied about 18 million barrels a day up from its 
quota of 16 million barrels 
other production estimates for march were libya 13 million 
barrels a day algeria 800000 barrels gabon 300000 barrels 
venezuela 19 million barrels ecuador 300000 barrels and 
indonesia 13 million barrels 
the international energy agency is an arm of the organization 
for economic cooperation and development made up of two dozen 
industrialized nations 
</TEXT>
