united airlines agreed to pay 775 million to 
settle lawsuits filed by continental airlines and others accusing 
united of unfair competition in the computerized reservations 
business according to documents made public tuesday 
united a subsidiary of chicagobased ual corp revealed the 
amount of the settlement in its annual report filed with the 
securities and exchange commission the settlement was reported 
last week by continental but the amount wasnt disclosed 
united spokeswoman sara dornacker said she could not comment on 
the settlement beyond what was contained in the sec filing 
in the filing united said the settlement concluded three cases 
that were initiated from sept 1985 to march 1989 by continental 
new york air inc frontier airlines and system one a computerized 
reservations system operated by continentals parent company texas 
air corp 
the plaintiffs contended united illegally monopolized or 
attempted to monopolize the computer reservations business or the 
air transportation business in various markets 
the settlement was reached last wednesday shortly before the 
beginning of jury deliberations in a 10week trial of continentals 
lawsuit in federal court 
continental had sought 336 million in damages claiming united 
programmed its computer reservations system to unfairly favor 
united flights over its competitors 
continental also accused united of overcharging it and other 
carriers for the reservation service 
last year american airlines settled similar allegations by 
continental for a reported 100 million 
united prevailed last december in a similar suit filed in 1984 
on behalf of 11 other airlines including usair an appeal in that 
case is pending 
