<TEXT>
dallas two newspapers went to court tuesday in a 
fight over syndicated comic strips and columns the latest twist in 
a bitter competition between the two dailies that cover the 
nations eighth largest city 
the dallas times herald is seeking at least 33 million in 
actual damages for what it considers a grab for monopoly by the 
dallas morning news and its parent ah belo corp 
the purchase of the syndicated features is not something done 
in an open competitive way times herald attorney frank jones 
told jurors during opening statements we think it was done in a 
way to destroy newspaper competition in dallas texas we think 
this is a case of preserving competition of newspapers in dallas 
county 
we think the evidence will show total arrogance and disregard 
by the dallas morning news jones said 
lawyers for the morning news countered that the paper was just 
competing and was willing to pay more for the contested features 
the only thing is we went out and competed with them for 
these features and paid a better price said harry reasoner an 
attorney for belo did we go out and pay a better price you 
betcha did we tortiously interfere and violate the law no 
at issue is a joint venture belo formed last year with universal 
press syndicate inc to develop syndicate features for television 
use 
part of their agreement was that universal press invoke a clause 
in its contract with the times herald allowing it to break off 
service the times herald lost 26 features distributed by universal 
press including dear abby erma bombeck and doonesbury 
the times herald contends the deal violates antitrust laws the 
morning news maintains its just fair competition 
testimony was scheduled to begin wednesday and the trial is 
expected to last more than a month 
in addition to actual damages the times herald is seeking 
unspecified punitive damages from its larger rival 
times herald attorney wayne fisher told prospective jurors that 
anticompetitive practices in the dallas media market threatened to 
drive the times herald out of business and could inflate the value 
of the morning news by as much as 500 million 
the morning news attracts about 60 percent of newspaper 
advertising and circulation in dallas court documents show 
its important to see if the dallas morning news can get away 
with the conduct theyve been getting away with over the past 
year fisher said if they do the dangerous possibility is the 
dallas times herald will not survive or the dallas morning news may 
get what the law calls monopoly power 
what the times herald is telling you is they would not like 
the morning news to compete for these features countered william 
sims an attorney for the morning news they dont want to up the 
ante and thats not what competition is all about we have the 
right to compete for these features 
the lawsuit is the latest legal salvo in the papers prolonged 
battle which in the past focused on challenging circulation 
features 
as a result of the universal belo joint venture the times 
herald also is asking the federal communications commission to 
revoke the license of belos wfaatv the toprated television 
station in dallas 
</TEXT>
